Introduction¶

For this project I chose to do the TMDb movie data dataset This data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue.

These are the questions I came up with and I plan to answer:

  • Which year were movies released the most?
  • Which genre is the most released?
  • Which movie gained the highest vote?

# We want to look at which were year the most movies released.
# Let us first group the movies by the year so that it makes getting the total easier.
release_count=tmdb_movies.groupby('release_year').count()['id']
release_count.head()
release_count.tail()

Name: id, dtype: int64
In [44]:
# # Because I might want to draw a bar graph again later, I will create a function that will allow me to do that
# so that I can use that function everytime I want to draw a graph
def bargraph_plot(x, xlabel, ylabel, title):
    """
    This function will plot a bargraph based on the parameters passed on:
    x (string): the series you want to plot
    xlabel (string): the label on the x-axis
    ylabel (string): the label on the y-axis
    title(string): the title of the graph
    """
    mplt.xlabel(xlabel, fontsize=20)
    mplt.ylabel(ylabel, fontsize=20)
    mplt.title(title, fontsize=20)
    plot = x.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(20,10))
    sns.set_style("darkgrid")
    return plot

# Now we can get a visualization of the number of movies released in the year
bargraph_plot(release_count, 'Release Year', 'Movie Total', 'Release Year vs Movie Total')
Out[44]:
<AxesSubplot:title={'center':'Release Year vs Movie Total'}, xlabel='release_year', ylabel='Movie Total'>

From the graph above we can see that the year with the highest movie release was 2014, with a total of 700 movies released in that year.

Research Question 2 (Which genre is the most released?)¶

In [45]:
# We first split the genre in the dataframe so we can look at them individually
genres_group = tmdb_movies.genres.str.split('|', expand = True)

# We want to get the count of each genre before printing it out
genres_count = genres_group[0].value_counts()
for a in range(1,5):
    b = genres_group[a].value_counts()
    genres_count = genres_count.add(b, fill_value=0)

# This will give you a visualization of what was coded above
bargraph_plot(genres_count, 'Genre Type', 'Movie Total', 'Movie Genre Count')
Out[45]:
<AxesSubplot:title={'center':'Movie Genre Count'}, xlabel='Genre Type', ylabel='Movie Total'>

From the graph above we can see that the genre that was the most released was Drama. This could mean that people love to watch more dramas than the other genres thats why its the one producers and directors prefer to create mor than the rest.

In [46]:
# Another way to visualize this question would be with a pie chart as this would make the visuals more nicer and clearer to view.
genres_count.plot(kind='pie', title='Movie Genre Count', ylabel='Genres', autopct='%1.0f%%', figsize=(15,15))
Out[46]:
<AxesSubplot:title={'center':'Movie Genre Count'}, ylabel='Genres'>

With a pie chart the visuals becomes more clear, we can even go on further to say that the top 3 movie genres are Drama(18%), Comedy(14%) and Thriller(11%).

Reasearch Question (Extras)¶

Lets plot correlation graphs so that we will be able to interpret how these variables relate to each other

  • Correlation Between Revenue and Vote Average
  • Correlation Between Budget and Vote Average
  • Correlation Between Release Year and Vote Average
In [51]:
# This code will draw the regplot and show it
revenue_vote = sns.regplot(x = "revenue", y = "vote_average", data = tmdb_movies)

# These codes are just a visual setup for our graph.
revenue_vote.set_title("Correlation Between Revenue and Vote Average",fontsize=20)
revenue_vote.set_xlabel("Revenue",fontsize=20)
revenue_vote.set_ylabel("Vote Average",fontsize=20)

sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(20,20)})
sns.set_style("darkgrid")

# This code will show the correlation between the revenue and vote average.
corr_plot = tmdb_movies.corr()
print("Correlation Between Revenue and Vote Average : ",corr_plot.loc['revenue','vote_average'])

Correlation Between Revenue and Vote Average :  0.17254138492900148

The correlation between revenue and vote average is positive (0.17), this means that the higher the vote average the higher the movie revenue.

The correlation between release year and vote average is negative (-0.11), this means that the vote average of movies does not depend on the release year.

Conclusions¶

  • For my analysis I kept the questions simple and I found that the year with the highest movie release was 2014, with a total of 700 movies. Followed by 2013 with 659 movies released and then 2015 with 629. I also saw a patern that over the years the number of movies increased significantly.
  • I also saw that the genre that was the most released movies was Drama with 4760 movies release, followed by Comedy with 3793 moveis released and then Thriller with 2907 movies released. With a pie chart we saw that the top 3 movie genres contributed to these percentage out of 100%: Drama(18%), Comedy(14%) and Thriller(11%)

  • Lastly the movie with the highest vote was "The Story of Film: An Odyssey" released in 2011 and it got an average vote of 9.2. followed by "The Mask You Live In" released in 2015 with an average vote of 8.9 "Black Mirror: White Christmas" released in 2014 with an average vote 8.8.

  • The correlation between revenue and vote average is positive (0.17), this means that the higher the vote average the higher the movie revenue.

  • The correlation between budget and vote average is a weak positive (0.081), this means that the higher the movie budget there's a chance that that movie will have a high vote average.
  • The correlation between release year and vote average is negative (-0.11), this means that the vote average of movies does not depend on the release year.

Throughout this dataset investigation I realised that there are so many aspects of this dataset that could be investigated and there is a possibility of asking a ton of questions. I just chose to ask the simple questions which made visualisation less complicated and quicker to come up with. I really just wanted to answer the simple questions that a non data analyst would ask, to try and get an uderstanding of the dataset.

Limitations¶

  • The dataste is not up to date so it won't give us accurate information as it can only give us information from 1960-2015.
  • Another limit is the fact that the budget and revenue column don't have a currencey unit so we can't really tell which country they were produced in.
  • I had to drop rows and columns that had missing and null values, and because of that it means my overall analysis was altered and therefore it can not be 100% accurate.
  • There was some time taken during the analysis process where i had to split the genre separated by '|' into list in order to calculate the total.
  • The dateset doesn't also tell us how the vote counts and vote average are calculated so there's no way of know how accurate it is
